Now let's talk about the SQL API. Here's the punchline up front. This is the exact same engine as the DataFrame API. Same optimizer, same execution, same speed. The only difference is that you write plain SQL instead of method calls. So if you already know SQL, you already know most of Spark. Pick whichever feels clearer for the problem in front of you, because under the hood they compile to the identical plan.

The first step is registration. Spark SQL works on tables and views, so you have to give your DataFrame a name before you can query it. Create temp view registers it for your current session. Create global temp view shares it across sessions. Save as table writes it into a persistent table you can come back to later. And once things are registered, the catalog lets you look around. Catalog dot list tables shows what tables exist, and catalog dot list columns shows the columns inside one. Now you have something to point a query at.

Then comes the query itself, built from the familiar clauses. Select chooses which columns come back. From names the table. Where filters rows before grouping. Group by buckets rows together. Having filters those groups after aggregating, which is the part people forget, where is before, having is after. Order by sorts the result. And limit and offset page through it, taking a slice from a given starting point. Learn the order these run in and SQL stops surprising you.

Next, combining tables. Inner join keeps only rows that match on both sides. Left join keeps everything from the left table. Full join keeps everything from both. Semi and anti joins filter the left table by whether a match exists on the right, without pulling the right table's columns in. Then the set operations. Union stacks two result sets together, and intersect keeps only the rows they share. And for structuring complex logic, you have CTEs, the WITH clause, which lets you name a subquery and reuse it, plus plain subqueries nested inside your query. CTEs are the secret to keeping big SQL readable.

Alongside joins sits aggregation, and this is where SQL really shines. The basic aggregates roll a column down to one number, average, sum, min and max, and count. But the real power is window functions. Row number assigns a sequential number within each group. Rank does the same but ties share a rank. Lag and lead let a row peek at the row before or after it, which is perfect for comparing a value to the previous day. And cume dist gives you the cumulative distribution, a row's relative standing in its group. Window functions compute across a set of rows without collapsing them, so you keep every row and add the calculation alongside.

Inside all of these, you'll lean on the built in functions. There are math functions like abs, ceiling, and floor, and round, square root, and log. String functions like concat and substring to slice and stitch text, and upper, lower, and trim to clean it. Date and time functions, current date and timestamp, and date add and format to shift and render dates. And because Spark columns can hold arrays, there are array functions too, array contains to test membership, and array sort and array union to manipulate them.

The last group is small but it causes more bugs than anything else, null semantics. In SQL, null means unknown, and unknown breaks normal comparisons. Null equals null is not true, it's null, because two unknowns aren't necessarily the same. That's why there's a special null safe equals operator, the one written as less-than equals greater-than, which does return true when both sides are null. To test for null you must use is null, never equals null. Coalesce returns the first non-null value from a list, which is how you supply defaults. And null if returns null when two values are equal, handy for turning sentinel values back into nulls. Keep these in mind and you'll dodge the most common silent mistakes in Spark SQL.

So that's the SQL API. Register your DataFrame as a view, write a query from the standard clauses, join and aggregate with the full power of window functions, and reach for the function library and the null rules inside your expressions. And never forget the big picture, this is the same fast engine as DataFrames wearing a SQL face, so use whichever one makes your intent clearest.
